The sharpest confrontation over executive power came at the Supreme Court. The administration sought to use the Alien Enemies Act of 1798 to deport Venezuelan migrants accused of gang ties on as little as twelve or twenty\uc0\u8209 four hours\'92 notice. Lower courts had required at least three weeks for detainees to challenge their removal. In A.A.R.P. v. Trump, the Supreme Court, by a 7\'962 vote, granted an injunction halting deportations under the proclamation and rejected the administration\'92s request to lift a temporary block. The justices emphasized that due process requires meaningful time to contest the government\'92s claims. In a separate case, the Court ruled 7\'962 against a policy of deporting alleged gang members without due process, again insisting on basic procedural rights. These decisions did not stop the administration from pursuing aggressive deportation policies, but they drew a line. Even in the name of security, the president could not erase the courts.\
