Yet the same Court heard arguments on another front that cut closer to the core of belonging. Three consolidated cases challenged Trump\'92s executive order seeking to end birthright citizenship for children born in the United States to non\uc0\u8209 citizen parents. The order, signed on his first full day back in office, directly contested the 14th Amendment\'92s guarantee that all persons born on U.S. soil are citizens. The administration also asked the Court to curb lower courts\'92 power to issue nationwide injunctions against presidential orders. The justices\'92 questions reportedly did not favor the administration, but the stakes were clear. If the order were upheld, citizenship itself would become contingent on parentage and status, and the judiciary\'92s ability to check the executive would narrow. The very definition of who belongs would shift from a constitutional promise to an administrative choice.\
