Below the Supreme Court, the administration pressed its advantage against the judiciary itself. A federal grand jury indicted Milwaukee County Judge Hannah Dugan for allegedly helping an undocumented man avoid ICE agents by allowing him to leave her courtroom through a jury door. She was arrested and publicly shamed, and the case was framed by officials as a warning to other judges. Dugan moved to dismiss the indictment, arguing that she was entitled to judicial immunity for her official acts and that the prosecution was unconstitutional. The indictment of a sitting judge for a courtroom decision sent a clear message. Judges who resist the administration\'92s immigration agenda could face personal criminal exposure.\
