Other judges, however, used their authority to shield individuals from what they saw as unlawful executive action. In South Dakota, a federal judge granted a preliminary injunction preventing the deportation of Priya Saxena, an Indian PhD graduate whose visa had been revoked over a minor traffic violation. The court barred DHS from arresting or detaining her without approval, calling the government\'92s actions likely unlawful and harmful. In New Jersey and Virginia, judges ordered the release of detained students and scholars, rejecting the government\'92s claims that their pro\uc0\u8209 Palestinian speech threatened foreign policy. These rulings did not stop the broader campaign to deport activists, but they carved out pockets of protection and affirmed that speech, even unpopular speech, remained protected.\
