While courts wrestled with the limits of power, the executive branch moved to reshape the information environment that citizens and the world use to judge that power. The most dramatic step came at Voice of America. The administration fired nearly 600 contractors, mostly journalists, representing more than a third of VOA\'92s workforce. Many were from authoritarian countries and now faced deportation because their visas were tied to their jobs. The firings defied a recent court order requiring the government to maintain strong news operations at VOA. The official rationale was \'93the government\'92s convenience.\'94 The practical effect was to weaken an independent, congressionally funded news outlet that had long broadcast American values abroad, and to signal that legal constraints would not stand in the way of remaking state media.\
