Against this tightening net, some institutional actors tried to widen the circle of belonging. In Omaha, voters elected John Ewing as the city\'92s first Black mayor, unseating a Republican incumbent in what observers saw as a local rejection of Trump\uc0\u8209 aligned politics. The Election Assistance Commission quietly sought public comment on new forms to monitor voting system manufacturers and on standardized financial reporting for election grants, steps that modestly strengthened transparency around election infrastructure. These were small moves, but they pointed toward a different use of state power: to broaden participation and ensure fair rules, rather than to narrow the electorate.\
