Information and memory, however, remained contested terrain. The administration fired Shira Perlmutter, head of the U.S. Copyright Office, shortly after she released a cautious report on AI and copyright that did not endorse sweeping government intervention. Her dismissal followed the firing of the Librarian of Congress for her involvement in diversity, equity, and inclusion programs. At the Pentagon, leaders ordered military academies to disregard race, ethnicity, and sex in admissions while allowing special consideration for athletic talent, and directed the removal of hundreds of books on diversity and gender from military and base school libraries worldwide. These moves narrowed the range of ideas and histories available to future officers and military families.\
